---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import NoteIllustration from "../../../components/NoteIllustration.astro";
import { SITE, notes } from "../../../data/site";

const note = notes.find((item) => item.slug === "a-working-demo-beats-a-deck")!;

const jsonLd = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    headline: note.title,
    description: note.summary,
    datePublished: note.date,
    author: {
      "@type": "Person",
      name: SITE.principal.name,
      url: SITE.principal.url
    },
    publisher: {
      "@type": "Organization",
      name: SITE.name,
      url: SITE.url
    }
  }
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title={note.title}
  description={note.summary}
  path={`/notes/${note.slug}/`}
  image={`/images/og/notes/${note.slug}.png`}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <p class="kicker">Notes · <time datetime={note.date}>{note.dateDisplay}</time></p>
    <h1>{note.title}</h1>
    <p>{note.summary}</p>
  </section>

  <article class="article-body" data-analytics-component="article_body">
    <p>
      We had a thesis about audiobooks: every app on the market treats AI
      as a feature. A synthetic voice here, a recommendation engine there,
      and a catalog that stays exactly as fixed as it was in 1995. We
      thought the more interesting question was what happens when AI is
      native to the product, when the story itself becomes malleable.
    </p>
    <p>
      We could have written that up as a strategy document. Instead we
      built <a class="text-link inline" href="/case-studies/bibo/" data-analytics-event="recirculation">Bibo</a>,
      a working demo you can open on your phone right now. That choice is
      the point of this note.
    </p>

    <h2>The thesis, in one tap</h2>
    <p>
      In Bibo, Moby Dick isn't one file. It's five complete versions on
      one tap: the classic narration, a shortened cut for a commute, a
      modern YA rewrite, a sci-fi retelling, and a Spanish literary
      translation, each fully voiced with AI narration. One asset became
      five products.
    </p>

    <NoteIllustration kind="multiplier" />

    <p>
      That's the pattern that matters beyond audiobooks. Any organization
      sitting on a content library (courses, a publishing backlist,
      research, marketing assets) is sitting on raw material for versions
      it has never shipped: other lengths, other formats, other languages,
      other audiences. AI turns a fixed catalog into a multiplier. The
      whole product changes with it; in Bibo, discovery became a feed,
      covers became a generated art system, and even the ad model became
      personalized audio.
    </p>

    <h2>Why not just write the deck?</h2>
    <p>
      Because a deck asks people to imagine, and imagination is where
      good theses go to die in committee. Everyone reads the same slide
      and pictures something different. Nobody can picture how it feels
      to drag a slider and hear the same story compress, or to type
      "retell this as a detective story in 1920s Chicago" and get one.
      A demo replaces twenty opinions about a hypothetical with one
      shared reaction to a real thing.
    </p>
    <p>
      A demo is also honest in a way a deck can't be. It has to survive
      contact with real constraints: what the AI actually produces, what
      the experience actually feels like, where the idea is weaker than
      the slide version. Finding that out in weeks, before serious money
      is committed, is the cheapest risk reduction available.
    </p>

    <h2>The part that changed recently</h2>
    <p>
      This used to be a quarter-long project with an agency invoice to
      match. Bibo went from concept to polished, self-contained demo in
      weeks: AI-assisted build, AI-generated narration, translations, and
      all fifty covers under human art direction. The cost of making an
      idea concrete has collapsed, which means the excuse for arguing
      about abstractions is gone. We wrote about that shift in
      <a class="text-link inline" href="/notes/production-got-cheap-judgment-didnt/" data-analytics-event="recirculation">Production
      got cheap. Judgment didn't.</a> This is what it looks like applied.
    </p>
    <p class="article-cta">
      Have a thesis that keeps stalling in meetings?
      <a class="text-link" href="/#contact" data-analytics-event="cta">Tell us what you're working
      on</a>. A short note is enough.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
